# Java Concurrency

## Virtual Threads (Java 21+)
- Use `Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()` for I/O-bound workloads
- Do NOT pool virtual threads -- each task gets its own
- Avoid `synchronized` blocks around blocking I/O (causes pinning); use `ReentrantLock` instead
- Detect pinning with JFR `VirtualThreadPinned` events
- Use `ScopedValue` instead of `ThreadLocal` for immutable per-task context

## Thread Safety Fundamentals
- Prefer `java.util.concurrent` collections over manual synchronization
- Use `AtomicInteger`, `LongAdder`, `AtomicReference` for lock-free single-variable operations
- Immutable objects are inherently thread-safe -- prefer them
- Safe publication via `volatile`, `final` fields, or `Atomic*` references

## Thread Pool Management
- Size CPU-bound pools to `Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors()`
- Use bounded work queues with explicit `RejectedExecutionHandler`
- Always shut down executors: `shutdown()` then `awaitTermination()`
- Name threads for observability: `new ThreadFactory` with descriptive names

## CompletableFuture
- Use `thenApply`/`thenCompose` for chaining, `exceptionally`/`handle` for errors
- Always supply a timeout: `orTimeout(duration)` or `completeOnTimeout(default, duration)`
- Do not block with `.get()` or `.join()` inside reactive/virtual-thread contexts

## Interruption Discipline
- Never swallow `InterruptedException` -- propagate or restore: `Thread.currentThread().interrupt()`
- Design tasks for cooperative cancellation via `Future.cancel(true)`
- Prefer `Lock.lockInterruptibly()` / `tryLock(timeout, unit)` over `synchronized`

## Backpressure
- Use bounded queues with `CallerRunsPolicy` for graceful load shedding
- Use `Semaphore` to cap concurrent access to shared resources
- For streaming: use `Flow` (Reactive Streams) API for backpressure

## Deadlock Prevention
- Establish global lock ordering
- Minimize lock scope and duration
- Use `tryLock` with timeouts instead of unconditional `lock()`
- Avoid nested synchronization across unrelated components

## Fit-for-Purpose Primitives
- `LongAdder` for high-contention counters
- `CopyOnWriteArrayList` for read-mostly observer lists
- `StampedLock` / `ReadWriteLock` for read-heavy data
- `CountDownLatch`, `Phaser`, `CyclicBarrier` for coordination

